    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-21T11:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-21T11:44:00-05:00" n="588"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/440: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia (<persName corresp="#p_MCE1"
                            type="from">Mitchell</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-21T16:00:00-00:44"
                            >December 21, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 22—2:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>110. Called on <persName corresp="#p_BE1">Barclay</persName> at 2:30. After
                    reciting to him the contents of the Department’s 76, December 19, 6 p.m.,
                        <persName corresp="#p_BE1">Barclay</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_GLA1">Grimes</persName>, who was also present, stated that they
                    could not act on a verbal representation but would be glad to give it
                    consideration if such information were submitted in the form of an <hi
                        rend="italic">aide-mémoire.</hi>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MCE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mitchell</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
